column441: If I had an obvious choice where my X values were both greater than either of my Y values  or vice versa  then I selected the X or Y with the greater values. However  if it wasn't an obvious choice  I would figure out what the other players would ideally select to have the best chance of winning. This would always trace back to the player who had the "obvious choice" (there was one player in every match who had an obvious choice) and everyone else's choices were ideally based off of theirs  so I could figure out how to select the highest possible number.

I think looking and seeing what I would predict the other colours to guess  based on what they think other colours would guess woul dhelp. Sometimes that led me to choose the option that had fewer tokens to gain because I imagined that other groups would see that option as more beneficial  depending on how everyone was likely to choose.

I chose the second largest token value  and predicted what action the other colors would choose based on the action I chose. From this method  I worked backwards  starting with my own choice  through the next color's choice my choice effected and the next color's choice after that until I made a full circle to my own choice. This method of working backwards from my own choice has worked every single time since I started using this strategy. Thus  I could predictably win the second largest amount of tokens every single match.

Assumption #1: People will choose the option with the largest return  this is always true when both highest returns correspond to one option (i.e. 24 and 28 are Xr and 5 and 8 are Yr). | Assumption # 2: #1 is violated when they Person R foresees G making a decision that will cause them to receive a very low return  in which case R will generally take the second highest return in order to not get  colloquially phrased  screwed over.

Try to find out the person like Green in display 3 among the four players  because no matter what decisions other players are maknig  Green in display 3 will always make the decision of XG. Then try to figure out how Green's decision is going to affect my points.

I would look at my choices and see where the highest numbers where. Then I would look at the choices of whichever color would be effecting mine and saw where their highest numbers where. If they fell in line with mine then I would choose based on that and if they would urge them differently I would choose based on what number I could get that was next highest in my table.

Based on the assumption that everyone wants to maximize their output  they will pick based on what their corresponding player picks and the line carries forth until you reach the one where either X or Y has higher payoffs for both  then go back down the chain to find your answer. Some people did not calculate however  thus leading occasional discrepancies
Hoping for the most while expect the other person to do the same

I briefly look at the options that other choices could have on my own gainings. I mostly selected the options using the ones that could lead me to earning the most tokens. However  if the two numbers were closer together on one option  even if they were lower than another option  I selected them because they still allowed me to earn a relatively decent amount of tokens.
Usually would try to judge what my partner would choose and then choose based off of that

I looked for the person with an obvious advantage (where X would always make more than Y or vice versa) and then decide how they would play  and base my decisions for other players and eventually myself on that decision; except when I was the lucky person who had a choice which was obviously advantageous.

In general I looked to the color that I was dependent on for guidance. Occassionally  when the values in one row for me were both higher than the values in the other row  I would select the row with the higher values without looking at any of the other colors since I knew that regardless the outcome  that row would have a greater yield. For the most part  I would try to guess what row the color that I was dependent on would want to select. If it was too hard to decide  I would look at the numbers for the color that the color I was depending on was also depending on. I assumed everyone had a similar technique throughtout and I did not change my way of deciding between actions even though occasionally my strategy did not work out as expected.
